           <div type="translation" xml:lang="fra" source="bib:Barth1903_01">
             <p rend="stanza" n="1">Lui, qui<gap reason="lost"/> fils de Śrī Vīravarman <supplied reason="subaudible">et</supplied> nullement inférieur en puissance, bien que le plus jeune frère de Śrī Bhavavarman ;</p>
              <p rend="stanza" n="2">Lui, Śrī Citrasena, qui possède toutes les marques de la majesté, a pris le nom de Śrī Mahendravarman lors de son sacre.</p>
              <p rend="stanza" n="3">Après avoir conquis toute la contrée, il a, sur ce mont, établi ce liṅga de Giriśa comme le signe de sa victoire.</p>
         </div>
           <div type="translation" resp="part:kuch"><!-- The translation is to be revised after checking the identical inscriptions. -->
              <p rend="stanza" n="1">Grandson of Śrī Sārvabhauma <supplied reason="subaudible">and</supplied> son of Śrī Vīravarman, in spite of being the youngest brother of Śrī Bhavavarman <supplied reason="subaudible">he was</supplied> not inferior in power.</p>
              <p rend="stanza" n="2">He whose mark was well known <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>āhatalakṣaṇaḥ</foreign></supplied> previously by name Śrī Citrasena received Śrī Mahendravarman as a name created <supplied reason="subaudible">at the time of his</supplied> crowning.</p>
              <p rend="stanza" n="3">Having conquered this entire country, <supplied reason="subaudible">he</supplied> installed on earth here a <foreign>liṅga</foreign> of Girīśa as his insignia of victory.</p>
           </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The three stanzas of this inscription are identical to those of five inscriptions, viz. K. 496, K. 497, K. 508, K. 1106 and K. 1190.</p> <!-- There is another identical inscription Ka 218 but it is not fully identified for the time being. -->
        <p>The first two stanzas of this inscription are identical to those of five inscriptions, viz. K. 509, K. 1102, K. 1174, K. 1339 and K. 1340.</p>
            <p>The first stanza of this inscription is identical to that of inscriptions K. 1173 and K. 1341.</p>
            <p>The restitution of the pāda a of the first stanza is based on K. 496, K. 508, K. 509, K. 1102, K. 1106, K. 1173, K. 1174, K. 1339 and K. 1340; the stanza in K. 497, K. 1190 and K. 1341 is fragmentary.</p>
         </div>
